"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778780","Department for Education","false","2017-11-06","<p>This department has not made any assessment of the effect of short-term custodial sentences on children separated from their mothers. However, the government has funded a contract worth over £1.4 million for Barnardo’s to operate the <em>i-HOP</em> service to share evidence on practice and advise commissioners and practitioners on the options available to support the families of offenders.</p><p>The law is clear that children are best looked after within their families, with their parents playing a full part in their lives, unless compulsory intervention in family life is necessary. The statutory guidance <em>Working Together to Safeguard Children</em> is clear that where a child is found to be in need, support should be provided to children and their families to improve their outcomes. <strong><br> </strong></p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","110070","2017-11-06T16:33:08.92Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778780/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778780/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778780/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-10-27","Mothers: Custodial Treatment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment she has made of the effect of short-term custodial sentences on children separated from their mothers.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","110071"
