"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778821","Department of Health","false","2017-11-06","<p>The Medical Director of NHS England, Professor Sir Bruce Keogh, responded to the then Parliamentary Under-Secretary for Public Health and Innovation (Nicola Blackwood) on 25 May 2017. A copy of that letter is attached.</p><p> </p><p>The IVF Expert Advisory Group has overseen good progress by NHS England and NHS Improvement toward developing a benchmark price for fertility services. The intention is that this will be ready for use by the National Health Service in the 2018/19 financial year. The commissioning guidance work is also intended to be available for the 2018/19 financial year.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","110125 ; 110145","2017-11-06T11:27:07.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778821/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778821/answer","Bruce Keogh reply to Nicola re NHS IVF 25 May 2017.pdf","Bruce Keogh reply to Nicola re NHS IVF 25 May 2017.pdf","PQ110125 attached doc.","PQ110125 attached doc.","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778821/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-10-27","In Vitro Fertilisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 12 October 2017 to Question 106061, on in vitro fertilisation, what response the then Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Health received from the Medical Director of NHS England.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","110144"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778822","Department of Health","false","2017-11-06","<p>The Medical Director of NHS England, Professor Sir Bruce Keogh, responded to the then Parliamentary Under-Secretary for Public Health and Innovation (Nicola Blackwood) on 25 May 2017. A copy of that letter is attached.</p><p> </p><p>The IVF Expert Advisory Group has overseen good progress by NHS England and NHS Improvement toward developing a benchmark price for fertility services. The intention is that this will be ready for use by the National Health Service in the 2018/19 financial year. The commissioning guidance work is also intended to be available for the 2018/19 financial year.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","110125 ; 110144","2017-11-06T11:27:08.033Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778822/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778822/answer","Bruce Keogh reply to Nicola re NHS IVF 25 May 2017.pdf","Bruce Keogh reply to Nicola re NHS IVF 25 May 2017.pdf","PQ110125 attached doc.","PQ110125 attached doc.","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778822/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-10-27","In Vitro Fertilisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 12 October 2017 to Question 106061, on in vitro fertilisation, when the commissioning guidance will be disseminated by NHS England to all clinical commissioning groups.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","110145"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778823","Department of Health","false","2017-11-06","<p>The UK Five Year Antimicrobial Resistance (AMR) strategy, 2013-2018, published in September 2013, had no associated funding to support implementation. All activity has been supported from within existing business plans of the organisations committed to tackling AMR.</p><p> </p><p>A record of what is spent directly on tackling AMR is not centrally maintained but examples of funded initiatives include NHS England’s use of Quality Premium and Commissioning for Quality and Innovation programmes to drive down inappropriate prescribing and a range of AMR research investments and awareness raising initiatives.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-11-06T11:30:32.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778823/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778823/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778823/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-10-27","Antibiotics: Drug Resistance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what budget was allocated to combating antibiotic-resistant bacteria (a) before 23 June 2017 and (b) currently.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","110154"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778824","Home Office","false","2017-11-02","<p>The Government is very clear that there will be no risks with public safety and there will be no gap in the emergency services’ communications provision.</p><p>It will ultimately be for the emergency services themselves to confirm they are content with the new ESN service and the existing Airwave system will continue until transition is complete. Greater clarity on the date ESN will be available is expected by the end of the year.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-11-02T17:19:49.473Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778824/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778824/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778824/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-27","Emergency Services Network","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what estimate she has made of the length of time for which Airwave and the emergency services network will run in parallel.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","110097"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778825","Home Office","false","2017-11-02","<p>The plan for delivery of the Emergency Services Network (ESN) includes an extensive period of testing and trials, culminating in one or more major operational trials. All test cases are derived from the ESN user requirements, which were developed with Emergency Services to ensure that the new network would perform as well, or better, than the Airwave service. User representatives are involved in all the test phases and will have final signoff on the suitability of ESN for mission critical use.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is very clear that there will be no risks with public safety and there will be no gap in the emergency services’ communications provision. It will ultimately be for the emergency services themselves to confirm they are content with the new ESN service and the existing Airwave system will continue until transition is complete.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-11-02T17:21:13.023Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778825/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778825/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778825/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-27","Emergency Services Network: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the effectiveness of the emergency services network compared with Airwave in transmitting mission-critical voice data in all operational circumstances.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","110077"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778826","Home Office","false","2017-11-01","<p>We actively monitor workflows at the border to ensure sufficient resources are in place to meet demand and will continue to do so throughout EU Exit negotiations and as the UK leaves the EU.</p><p> </p><p>We are considering a range of options for the UK’s future immigration system and will be outlining further details of the new system later in the year.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-11-01T13:38:47.34Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778826/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778826/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778826/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-27","Immigration Controls: Costs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what estimate she has made of the additional expenditure required to control levels of immigration at the UK border after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","110103"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778827","Home Office","false","2017-11-01","<p>The final police settlement for 2017/18 was laid in Parliament on 1<sup>st</sup> February 2017. The final police settlement was debated and agreed in the House of Commons on 22<sup>nd</sup> February.</p><p>Overall police spending, including council tax precept, is protected in real terms for the period of Spending Review 2015. Each PCC who maximised their precept income in 2015/16 and 2016/17 are receiving at least cash flat direct resource funding in 2017/18 when compared to 2015/16.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-11-01T17:07:07.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778827/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778827/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778827/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-27","Police: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 11 October 2017 to Question 105689, on police: finance, whether her Department holds the information requested in Question 105689.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","110057"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778828","Home Office","false","2017-11-01","<p>The Home Office works closely with local authorities across Great Britain through regional Strategic Migration Partnerships to ensure all unaccompanied children arriving here receive the care and support they need. We encourage local authorities to offer suitable placements, regardless of the child’s route of arrival.</p><p>The National Transfer Scheme for unaccompanied children is already based on a regional model and was established to promote a fairer distribution of caring responsibilities across the country in a way that protects the best interests of all children.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-11-01T11:24:42.06Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778828/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778828/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778828/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-27","Refugees: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the potential merits of establishing more localised administration of the Dubs Scheme based in the regions and constituent parts of the UK.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","110042"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778829","Home Office","false","2017-11-01","<p>The Migration Advisory Committee in their review of Tier 2 in December 2015 strongly supported the introduction of the Immigration Skills Charge and was clear that it should apply to the public sector, including the NHS.</p><p> </p><p>The rate and scope of the charge, including exemptions from the charge, were agreed in discussion with other government departments, including the Department of Health.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-11-01T11:25:23.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778829/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778829/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778829/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-27","Psychiatry: Migrant Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 24 October 2017 to Question 107878, on the international skills charge, what discussions she has had with the Secretary of State for Health about the financial effect on mental health trusts of the introduction of the international skills charge for psychiatrists who do not have a PhD and who are on tier 2 visas.","false","Biography information for Barbara Keeley","Worsley and Eccles South","Barbara Keeley","110055"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778830","Home Office","false","2017-11-02","<p>Home Office Ministers have regular meetings as part of the process of policy developments and delivery. As was the case with the previous administrations, it is not the Government’s practice to provide details of all such meetings.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-11-02T17:16:29.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778830/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778830/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778830/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-27","Emergency Services Network: Radio Frequencies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what representations she has received on the reserved radio spectrum for the emergency services network.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","110062"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778831","Home Office","false","2017-11-01","<p>The new Emergency Services Network (ESN) will provide the dedicated teams who work so hard protecting the public and saving lives with the most advanced communications system of its kind anywhere in the world.</p><p> </p><p>The Emergency Services Mobile Communications Programme (ESMCP) is working with both Transport for London (TFL), Crossrail, and other bodies across Britain to ensure that there is coverage in underground stations, metro systems, back office areas and tunnels that is as good as, or better than, that offered by the current Airwave solution.</p><p> </p><p>This is cutting-edge technology and we have always said that we will not be taking any risks with public safety and so Airwave will continue until the emergency services have completed transition on to ESN.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-11-01T17:10:18.243Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778831/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778831/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778831/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-27","Emergency Services Network","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how the emergency services network will operate underground; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","110063"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778832","Home Office","false","2017-11-01","<p>The Emergency Services Mobile Communications Programme (ESMCP) remains committed to providing the Emergency Service users the time they need to transition safely to the Emergency Service Network (ESN) and are working on the assumption of a continuing need for a 27 month user transition period once mobilisation has been completed.</p><p>The Government is very clear that there will be no risks taken with public safety and there will be no gap in the emergency services’ communications provision.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-11-01T17:08:11.113Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778832/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778832/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778832/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-27","Emergency Services Network: Testing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will continue to facilitate the use of Airwave until the emergency services have confirmed that the emergency services network has been rigorously tested.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","110064"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778833","Home Office","false","2017-11-01","<p>Airwave provides a fully managed service to the three Emergency Services. Negotiations by Airwave on the legacy core transmission network with any of its subcontractors are managed by Airwave.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-11-01T17:11:05.403Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778833/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778833/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778833/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-27","Emergency Services Network: Motorola Solutions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the outcome was of negotiations with Motorola on the legacy core transmission network.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","110065"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778834","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-11-02","<p>The Department for Work &amp; Pensions (DWP) interprets this question as relating to State Pension claims.</p><p> </p><p>DWP does not retain information about the amount of State Pension payments which have been delayed in the last 12 months for more than (a) one, (b) two and (c) three months.</p><p> </p><p>DWP is not able to ascertain whether a State Pension payment has been delayed as this is dependant on a number of factors, such as the date of entitlement, date when the customer requests payment to be made and whether a customer has put off (deferred) making their claim.</p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman",,"2017-11-02T12:12:06.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778834/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778834/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778834/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-10-27","State Retirement Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many state pension payments have been delayed in the last 12 months for more than (a) one, (b) two and (c) three months.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","110072"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778835","Department for International Development","false","2017-11-03","<p>The UK continues to invest in education for women and girls affected by the crisis in Syria. We helped launch UNICEF’s No Lost Generation Initiative, which provides education, protection, and mental health support for children in Syria and neighbouring countries. In 2016/2017 alone, DFID helped provide over 350,000 children in Syria with access to formal primary education, half of whom were girls. In addition, over 80,000 children, including girls, were provided with access to non-formal education. DFID also helped to provide over 3,500 people in Syria with technical and vocational training, including women.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-11-03T17:48:28.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778835/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778835/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778835/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-10-27","Syria: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department is taking to contribute to achieving UN Sustainable Development Goal 4, on inclusive and quality education for all and promoting lifelong learning with regard to women and girls in Syria.","false","Biography information for Wera Hobhouse","Bath","Wera Hobhouse","110069"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778836","Department for International Development","false","2017-11-01","<p>DFID’s Annual Report and Accounts, and Statistics on International Development publication, provide annual, comprehensive organisational information to parliament and taxpayers. In addition, DFID publishes detailed project data and documents, details of all payments over £500, and information on programmes, procurement, people and ministerial activity.</p><p>Our recent Supplier Review introduced new, stringent criteria for transparency of supplier information to drive down costs along supply chains. DFID intends to put even more information in the public domain, including policies on day rates paid to consultants and annual league tables of supplier performance.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-11-01T17:57:18.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778836/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778836/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778836/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-10-27","Department for International Development: Disclosure of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, with reference her the oral contribution to the International Development Committee on 24 October 2017, if she will set out the transparency practices used by her Department.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","110054"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778837","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-11-06","<p>Public protection is our top priority and we will take all necessary action to make sure the probation system is reducing reoffending and preventing future victims.</p><p>There is a contractual mechanism for dealing with recommendations made in HM Inspectorate of Probation reports and, as a result, we expect Community Rehabilitation Companies (CRCs) to action all HMI Probation recommendations where reasonably practicable. Contract Management Teams give high priority to ensuring that these are followed through, and ensure that the actions are successful in addressing the points raised.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-11-06T13:04:24.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778837/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778837/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778837/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-27","Community Rehabilitation Companies: Gloucestershire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps the Government has taken to address the recommendations of the report on the Community Rehabilitation Company activity in Gloucestershire published by HM Inspectorate of Probation on 31 August 2017.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","110034"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778838","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-11-06","<p>Powers of arrest are not granted to private security firms, they are granted to Approved Enforcement Agencies (AEA) as well as to HMCTS Civilian Enforcement Officers and the Police. These are not new powers. They have been in use for many years across the country.</p><p> </p><p>These powers apply to arrests relating to debt and community penalty breaches, following the issue of a Warrant of Arrest from the criminal courts. The use of AEAs to execute warrants of arrest is overseen by Her Majesty’s Courts and Tribunals Service.</p><p> </p><p>A procurement process is currently underway which will result in the establishment of new AEA contracts. That procurement process is also exploring the potential to further extend the volume of arrest warrants executed by AEAs. HMCTS will fully evaluate all proposals submitted by potential AEAs as part of the bidding process before making a final decision on this.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-11-06T17:34:04.81Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778838/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778838/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778838/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-27","Security: Private Sector","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps are being taken to ensure appropriate use of powers of arrest which are to be granted to private security firms; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","110035"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778839","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-11-06","<p>Every prison has an agreed safe, decent and secure operating level (SDSOL) which reflects the category of prison and the types of prisoners held. The SDSOL is central to the delivery of the regime in every prison. In addition, this Government is on target to recruit an additional 2500 Prison Officers by December 2018 to improve safety and offender management in custody. Since April 2017 Governors have been empowered to manage workforce planning locally and use this flexibility to set their own staffing arrangements.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-11-06T17:35:00.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778839/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778839/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778839/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-27","Prison Officers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether his Department has different prison officer to prisoner ratio targets for different categories of prison; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Imran Hussain","Bradford East","Imran Hussain","110036"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778840","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-11-06","<p>The roll out of Body Worn Video Cameras was completed in June 2017 and there are currently nearly 6,000 in use across the estate. Body worn cameras will considerably aid safety in prisons, acting as a visible deterrent against violence and assisting in prosecutions against those who commit crimes in jails.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-11-06T13:03:37.83Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778840/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778840/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778840/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-27","Prison Officers: Cameras","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what progress has been made on the roll-out of body-worn cameras for prison officers.","false","Biography information for Imran Hussain","Bradford East","Imran Hussain","110050"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778841","Home Office","false","2017-11-01","<p>Data on outcomes, including out of court outcomes, for crimes are published quarterly by the Home Office. Outcomes data for violent crimes in the last three years can be obtained via the open data tables available here:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/police-recorded-crime-open-data-tables" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/police-recorded-crime-open-data-tables</a></p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-11-01T17:08:59.69Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778841/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778841/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778841/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-27","Crimes of Violence: Reparation by Offenders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many incidents of violent crime were disposed of out of court in each of the last three years; and in how many of those cases restorative justice was used.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","110109"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778842","Leader of the House","false","2017-11-01","<p>I confirm that the new convention I announced in the House on 26 October will apply retrospectively to resolutions of the House passed on Opposition Days earlier this Session.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2017-11-01T17:11:06.603Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778842/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778842/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778842/answer",,,,,"34","Leader of the House","Leader of the House","2017-10-27","Opposition Days","1","House of Commons","To ask the Leader of the House, pursuant to the Written Statement of 26 October 2017, on Opposition Day debates, HCWS199, if that policy applies retrospectively to resolutions of the House passed earlier this Session.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","110093"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778844","Scotland Office","false","2017-11-01","<p>Like all departments, the Scotland Office is planning for a number of EU Exit scenarios to make sure we are ready on Day 1.</p><p> </p><p>Over £250m of additional funding has been approved across a number of departments in 2017/18 to prepare for Brexit. The Scotland Office has received additional funding this year, and has reprioritised to meet new pressures arising from Brexit preparations. Additional funding received from the reserve for 2017/18 will be set out at Supplementary Estimates and decisions on funding in future years will be confirmed at a later date.</p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2017-11-01T17:32:13.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778844/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778844/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778844/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2017-10-27","Scotland Office: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, how much funding his Department has allocated to prepare for the contingency of no deal being reached in negotiations between the UK and the EU.","false","Biography information for Wes Streeting","Ilford North","Wes Streeting","110043"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778845","Department for Transport","false","2017-11-01","<p>The draft Accessibility Action Plan is currently being consulted upon, the Department will review and consult on best practice guidance for taxi and PHV licensing authorities, which will include strengthened recommendations on supporting accessible services.</p><p> </p><p>The statutory guidance issued under section 177 of the Policing and Crime Act 2017 will not include a requirement for all taxi and private hire vehicle (PHV) drivers to undertake disability equality training as this is beyond the scope of the legislation which is to “protect children, and vulnerable individuals who are 18 or over, from harm.”</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-11-01T14:12:16.91Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778845/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778845/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778845/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-10-27","Taxis: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether proposed statutory guidance on taxi and private hire vehicle licensing will include a requirement for all drivers to undertake disability equality training.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","110091"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778846","Department for Transport","false","2017-11-01","<p>When fully open from December 2019, all of the stations on the Elizabeth line will be step-free to platform level with clear signage and information to ensure that all passengers can get around the stations quickly and easily.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-11-01T12:15:43.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778846/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778846/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778846/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-10-27","Crossrail Line: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent assessment he has made of the levels of accessibility for disabled people planned for Crossrail stations.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","110041"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778847","Department for Transport","false","2017-11-01","<p>The Government’s Statement of Funds Available for Control Period 6 (2019-2024) published on 12 October includes funding for continued investment in the accessibility of the railway.</p><p> </p><p>We will confirm the way in which we will deliver improvements to accessibility later in the year.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-11-01T11:46:23.553Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778847/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778847/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778847/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-10-27","Railway Stations: Access","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what discussions he has had with the Chancellor of the Exchequer on a new round of access for all funding to improve railway station access for the disabled and other vulnerable users.","false","Biography information for James Cartlidge","South Suffolk","James Cartlidge","110113"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778848","Department for Transport","false","2017-11-06","<p>The UK’s roads are among the safest in the world and there is no evidence to suggest that there is a widespread road safety risk relating to people driving inappropriately due to a notifiable medical condition. The majority of individuals notify the Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency (DVLA) of medical conditions as they are required to. The DVLA also accepts notifications from the police and health care professionals. The Government therefore has no plans to carry out a formal consultation as suggested.</p><p> </p><p>The processes for notifying a medical condition to the DVLA are kept under review. Potential improvements to processes are fully explored and implemented, where appropriate. The DVLA has made improvements to raise awareness of the importance of notifying a medical condition which may affect fitness to drive. Officials have worked closely with doctors and other medical professionals to publish revised guidance. The DVLA has also introduced an electronic service which allows drivers to notify certain medical conditions online. Letters to customers and medical professionals have been improved, helping to ensure that the DVLA receives the information it needs as quickly as possible.</p><p> </p><p>The Government believes that there are already sufficient powers available to the relevant prosecution authorities.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-11-06T14:13:19.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778848/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778848/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778848/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-10-27","Driving: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to the Glasgow bin lorry crash of 22 December 2014, if he will take steps to undertaken a consultation on (a) how to ensure the completeness and accuracy of information available to the DVLA for the purposes of making fitness to drive licensing decisions and (b) increasing the penalties and altering the mode of prosecution for contravention of section 94 of the Road Traffic Act 1988.","false","Biography information for Martin Whitfield","East Lothian","Martin Whitfield","110098"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778849","Department for Transport","false","2017-11-01","<p>Marks Tey station currently has step free access to both platforms but no step free interchange between them.</p><p> </p><p>Much of our station infrastructure is Victorian and is therefore not accessible to many disabled passengers. In recognition of the scale of the problem there has been, over successive administrations, a gradual improvement approach and stations have been selected for funding through a prioritisation and assessment process.</p><p> </p><p>All of the available Access for All funding has now been allocated to projects until Spring 2019. We are committed to continuing to invest in the accessibility of the railway after 2019 and will confirm the way in which we will deliver this later in the year.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-11-01T11:47:04.653Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778849/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778849/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778849/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-10-27","Marks Tey Station","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of accessibility at Marks Tey railway station.","false","Biography information for James Cartlidge","South Suffolk","James Cartlidge","110100"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778850","Department for Transport","false","2017-11-03","<p>The Government is considering carefully all the potential implications arising from the UK’s exit from the EU. Securing liberal market access to EU markets is a high priority for the Department for Transport.</p><p> </p><p>The importance of air services to the UK economy is recognised across Government and we work closely with the aviation sector to ensure its ongoing success. This includes through securing a good deal with the EU.</p><p> </p><p>These discussions, as a matter of common sense, also include consideration of possible alternatives to a negotiated agreement, to ensure that no matter the outcome flights will continue.</p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-11-03T12:52:16.97Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778850/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778850/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778850/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-10-27","Aviation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of no deal with the EU on the aviation sector when the UK leaves the EU; what plans he has to support the aviation sector in the event of no deal with the EU; and what discussions he has had with representatives from the aviation sector about the effect on the aviation sector of no deal with the EU.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","110151"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778851","Wales Office","false","2017-11-02","<p>There has been, and will continue to be, constructive engagement between the UK Government and the Welsh Government on the issue of EU Exit. On 30 October, the Prime Minister and I met with the First Minister, and last month the First Secretary of State and I also met with him.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is committed to ensuring that withdrawal from the EU is a successful and smooth process for all parts of the UK, and we are conscious that a significant proportion of the traffic at some ports is not currently subject to customs controls. We want to ensure that traffic continues to flow freely at all UK ports and airports, including Holyhead, and we will seek to ensure that customs arrangements and mechanisms are as frictionless as possible, and that trade fluidity is maintained. Officials in the Wales Office and colleagues across Government are working with port operators and other stakeholders in Wales to support the smooth and orderly implementation of these new arrangements.</p><p> </p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2017-11-02T15:12:46.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778851/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778851/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778851/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2017-10-27","Holyhead Port: Infrastructure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what discussions he has had with the Welsh Government on the potential implications of the UK leaving the Customs Union on changes to levels of traffic and usage at the port in Holyhead requiring additional infrastructure in and around that port.","false","Biography information for Hywel Williams","Arfon","Hywel Williams","110052"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778852","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-11-06","<p>The Department for Work &amp; Pensions (DWP) does not retain data for the proportion of online applications for State Pension which were processed and paid in (a) less than one, (b) less than two, (c) less than three and (d) more than three months.</p><p> </p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman",,"2017-11-06T11:35:19.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778852/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778852/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778852/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-10-27","State Retirement Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many and what proportion of online applications for state pension were processed and paid in (a) less than one, (b) less than two, (c) less than three and (d) more than three months.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","110067"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778853","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-11-02","<p>The Department for Work &amp; Pensions (DWP) interprets this question as relating to State Pension claims.</p><p> </p><p>DWP does not retain information about the amount of State Pension payments which have been delayed in the last 12 months.</p><p> </p><p>DWP is not able to ascertain whether a State Pension payment has been delayed as this is dependant on a number of factors, such as the date of entitlement, date when the customer requests payment to be made and whether a customer has put off (deferred) making their claim.</p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman",,"2017-11-02T12:03:32.073Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778853/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778853/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778853/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-10-27","State Retirement Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many state pension payments have been delayed in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","110068"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778854","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-11-01","<p>The delivery of the Universal Credit programme has undergone a number of changes since the 2013 NAO report.</p><p> </p><p>The Universal Credit programme is already subject to a robust regime of internal and external scrutiny, including oversight from the Work and Pensions Select Committee, the Public Accounts Committee, the National Audit Office and the Infrastructure and Projects Authority. We have also published our transparency policy and recently published a suite of reports, analysis and statistics which gives an open an honest overview of all aspects of the programme.</p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-11-01T15:32:12.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778854/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778854/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778854/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-10-27","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps he has taken to address the good news culture in his Department in relation to the roll-out of universal credit, which was identified by the National Audit Office in its report universal credit: early progress published in September 2013.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","110075"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778855","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-11-02","<p>The Average Speed of Answer for the Pensions Helpline was 1 minute and 28 seconds in September 2017.</p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman",,"2017-11-02T12:07:23.573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778855/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778855/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778855/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-10-27","State Retirement Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the average waiting time is for calls made to the state pension helpline.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","110073"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778856","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-11-06","<p>The Department for Work &amp; Pensions (DWP) informs customers of their eligibility to claim State Pension approximately four months prior to reaching pension age. A BR330R – State Pension invitation pack is sent by post to the customer’s address held by DWP. This provides details of how a customer can make a claim for State Pension by either (a) making a claim online, (b) by telephone or (c) completing a clerical claim form. Further information regarding claiming State Pension can be obtained from GOV.UK</p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman",,"2017-11-06T11:38:16.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778856/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778856/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778856/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-10-27","State Retirement Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether it is his Department's policy to notify people when they are eligible to receive their state pension.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","110074"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778857","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-11-01","<p>The latest available information on alternative payment arrangements can be found at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/universal-credit-statistics-on-alternative-payment-arrangements" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/universal-credit-statistics-on-alternative-payment-arrangements</a>.</p><p> </p><p>The latest available information on managed payments to landlords can be found at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/universal-credit-29-apr-2013-to-10-aug-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/universal-credit-29-apr-2013-to-10-aug-2017</a>.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-11-01T15:35:26.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778857/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778857/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778857/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-10-27","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many alternative payment arrangements have been made in each month since April 2013.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","110061"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778858","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-11-06","<p>The information requested is not available.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-11-06T12:17:13.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778858/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778858/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778858/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-10-27","Universal Credit: Homelessness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 20 October 2017 to Question 108189, on universal credit: homelessness, what the (a) maximum and (b) average length of time it has been to complete the validation process in circumstances where the claimant does not have sufficient documentary evidence to verify their identity in the latest period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","110142"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778859","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-11-06","<p>In addition to the support set out in the Answer of 20 October 2017 to Question <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2017-10-17/108189/" target="_blank">108189</a>, we are continuously reviewing and improving the service for vulnerable people who claim UC. This includes how they are identified and supported, either internally or via referral to local services delivered in partnership with other relevant agencies and organisations. Where claimants have no capability to make or manage their claim on-line, telephone and face to face support is available, with staff also able to refer to specialist provision.</p><p> </p><p>The Department recognises that as a priority, claimants who have recently become homeless will need time to try and resolve their accommodation issues. During this time, if a Work Coach determines that it is unreasonable to impose any work related activities on the claimant, they may temporarily switch off work search and work availability requirements in the claimant commitment and direct the claimant to concentrate on seeking additional support through various homeless organisations instead.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-11-06T12:06:20.58Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778859/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778859/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778859/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-10-27","Universal Credit: Homelessness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 20 October 2017 to Question 108189, on universal credit: homelessness, whether there is any additional support offered to homeless people applying for universal credit.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","110143"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778860","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-11-06","<p>DWP continue to analyse the reality of rent arrears in Universal Credit. The department will also continue to publish information on performance and experience of the service.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-11-06T18:16:10.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778860/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778860/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778860/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-10-27","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 20 October 2017 to Question 108182, on universal credit, if he will publish the research referred to in that Answer.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","110131"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778861","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-11-06","<p>The maximum amount of an advance following a new claim to Universal Credit is 50% of a claimant’s total indicative award or 100% where the claimant’s payment due date has passed. We think that the maximum amount of 50% strikes the right balance between supporting claimants with their living expenses and ensuring they have the ability to repay. No assessment has been made of how advances interact with poverty rates because advances are designed to meet a claimant’s immediate short term financial need and are not intended to address poverty rates. Universal Credit is helping to improve people’s lives by making work pay by moving people into work and allowing individuals to keep more of their earned income.</p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","110135 ; 110136","2017-11-06T11:54:26.533Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778861/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778861/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778861/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-10-27","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 20 October 2017 to Question 108191, on universal credit, what the maximum value is of an advanced payment.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","110134"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778862","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-11-06","<p>The maximum amount of an advance following a new claim to Universal Credit is 50% of a claimant’s total indicative award or 100% where the claimant’s payment due date has passed. We think that the maximum amount of 50% strikes the right balance between supporting claimants with their living expenses and ensuring they have the ability to repay. No assessment has been made of how advances interact with poverty rates because advances are designed to meet a claimant’s immediate short term financial need and are not intended to address poverty rates. Universal Credit is helping to improve people’s lives by making work pay by moving people into work and allowing individuals to keep more of their earned income.</p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","110134 ; 110136","2017-11-06T11:54:26.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778862/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778862/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778862/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-10-27","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 20 October 2017 to Question 108191, on universal credit, what rationale was used to establish the current maximum value of advanced payments.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","110135"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778863","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-11-06","<p>The maximum amount of an advance following a new claim to Universal Credit is 50% of a claimant’s total indicative award or 100% where the claimant’s payment due date has passed. We think that the maximum amount of 50% strikes the right balance between supporting claimants with their living expenses and ensuring they have the ability to repay. No assessment has been made of how advances interact with poverty rates because advances are designed to meet a claimant’s immediate short term financial need and are not intended to address poverty rates. Universal Credit is helping to improve people’s lives by making work pay by moving people into work and allowing individuals to keep more of their earned income.</p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","110134 ; 110135","2017-11-06T11:54:26.643Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778863/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778863/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778863/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-10-27","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 20 October 2017 to Question 108191, on universal credit, what assessment he has made of the effect the maximum value of advanced payments has on the level of poverty experienced by universal credit applicants.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","110136"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778864","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-11-06","<p>The Personal Support Package was introduced from April 2017 to provide personalised and tailored support for people with health conditions and disabilities. Some elements such as the Health and Work Conversation, began rolling out earlier.</p><p> </p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-11-06T11:44:43.153Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778864/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778864/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778864/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-10-27","Long Term Unemployed People: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 16 October 2017 to Question 107217, on long-term unemployed people: training, when the personal support package was introduced.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","110126"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778865","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-11-06","<p>The national offer within the Personal Support Package includes the recruitment of 204 Community Partners, 102 Small Employer Advisers (to deliver the Small Employer Offer) and 300 additional Disability Employment Advisers across all Jobcentre Plus districts, the national roll out of the Health and Work Conversation, and places on specialist contracted employment support for new eligible ESA Work Related Activity Group and UC Limited Capability for Work claimants that volunteer.</p><p> </p><p>The package also includes specific regional elements such as the introduction of Peer Support job clubs to 71 Jobcentre Plus areas. We have also rolled out a number of small Proof of Concepts that could be scaled up to trials.</p><p> </p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-11-06T11:41:44.843Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778865/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778865/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778865/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-10-27","Long Term Unemployed People: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 16 October 2017 to Question 107217, on long-term unemployed people: training, whether the new personal support package is being rolled out nationally.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","110124"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778866","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-11-01","<p>Claimants can not voluntarily switch from legacy benefits to Universal Credit.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-11-01T15:29:19.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778866/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778866/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778866/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-10-27","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the (a) effect on claimants and (b) extent of the practice of encouraging claimants to voluntarily switch from legacy benefits to universal credit.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","110119"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778867","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-11-06","<p>DWP has not conducted research into the impact of UC on household poverty. Estimates of the number and proportion of individuals in relative low income are published in the National Statistics Households Below Average Income (HBAI) series, available here:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/households-below-average-income-hbai--2" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/households-below-average-income-hbai--2</a>.</p><p> </p><p>The latest annual publication was on 2015/16 data and we will continue to monitor relative low income rates in future publications. The Prime Minister has set out clearly that she is committed to building a country that works for everyone – not just the privileged few. We know that work is the best route out of poverty, and Universal Credit is designed to strengthen incentives for parents to move into and progress in work. The impact of Universal Credit cannot be considered in isolation– it is a key component of a broader strategy to move Britain to a higher wage, lower welfare, lower tax society.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-11-06T11:48:43.483Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778867/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778867/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778867/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-10-27","Poverty","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 20 October 2017 to Question 108182, on universal credit, whether his Department has conducted any similar research on the nature of household poverty.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","110132"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778868","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-11-02","<p>The UK’s publicly funded fusion research is led by the UK Atomic Energy Authority (UKAEA).</p><p> </p><p>UKAEA receives direct funding from the Euratom Research and Training Programme (£57.3 m in 2017/18 and £55.1 m in 2018/19) primarily for research carried out at the Joint European Torus (JET).</p><p> </p><p>UKAEA also receives grant funding for fusion research from the Engineering and Physical Sciences Research Council (£26.1m in 2017/18 and £27.0m in 2018/19).</p><p> </p><p>UKAEA also receives additional funding from the UK Government for specific projects which have been worth £5.4m so far in 2017/18. Firm allocations for the financial year 2018/19 and beyond have not yet been made.</p><p> </p><p>The UK is also a member of Fusion for Energy, the EU based partnership delivering its contribution to the International Thermonuclear Experimental Reactor, the next generation international fusion project in France. The EU expects to contribute €380m in 2018 and €427m in 2019 to ITER. The EU budget beyond 2020 is subject to agreement with EU member states.</p><p> </p><p>Information relating to private sector investment in fusion in the UK is not available.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-11-02T10:33:31.323Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778868/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778868/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778868/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-10-27","Nuclear Fusion: Research","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what budget has been allocated to research on nuclear fusion up to 29 March 2019.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","110155"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778869","Department for International Trade","false","2017-11-07","<p>When recruiting civil servants, managers are able to review candidates’ previous experience and career history as part of our recruitment policies and campaigns. As a result, the Department for International Trade (DIT) has a strong and capable trade policy team which has grown significantly since its establishment in July 2016 and is continuing to grow.</p><p> </p><p>DIT has almost 3,600 staff, including our ‘Trade Policy Group’ of over 400 people.</p><p> </p><p>Over the summer, we also recruited internationally recognised expert Crawford Falconer as DIT’s Chief Trade Negotiation Adviser and Second Permanent Secretary. With more than 25 years of public service experience in trade and foreign affairs, Falconer will support the establishment of a world-class trade negotiation function and lead the development of a new International Trade profession for trade negotiators and will bolster the Civil Service’s trade negotiation skills.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-11-07T16:54:16.323Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778869/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778869/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778869/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-10-27","Trade Agreements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how many staff in his Department have negotiated and completed a free trade agreement; and with which countries those agreements were negotiated.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","110153"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778870","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-11-03","<p>The Department is continuing to recruit the brightest and the best from across the civil service, the wider public sector and the private sector. Of the staff on the DExEU system as of 30 September 2017, the average length of service in the Civil Service was 6 years, 4 months and 22 days.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The Department for Exiting the European Union is drawing together expertise from a wide range of departments where there is specific relevant knowledge. The Department has sourced a large proportion of experienced staff from across Whitehall on a loan basis and a number of secondees from the private sector and the wider public sector. All departments are equipping themselves with the resources they need to get the best deal for the UK.</p><p> </p>","Wycombe","Mr Steve Baker",,"2017-11-03T17:24:46.15Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778870/answer","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778870/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778870/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-10-27","Department for Exiting the European Union: Length of Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what estimate his Department has made of the average length of service in the civil service of staff employed by his Department.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","110139"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778871","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-11-03","<p>The Department for Exiting the European Union has spent a total of £46.147m on running the Department since the official creation of the Department on 14 July 2016, the day after Rt Hon David Davis was appointed as Secretary of State, until the 30 September 2017. The total amount can be broken down into £23.707m of expenditure during the 2016-17 financial year, which excludes the costs incurred by the Europe Unit of the Cabinet Office and the Europe Directorate of the Foreign and Commonwealth Office prior to 14 July 2016, and is therefore £1.548m below the total figure published in the Department’s ARA. A more detailed breakdown of 16/17 expenditure is available in the Department’s ARA.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Also included in £46.147m is £22.44m of total expenditure from the start of 2017-18 financial year until 30 September, however, this figure remains subject to audit.</p><p> </p>","Wycombe","Mr Steve Baker",,"2017-11-03T17:28:32.57Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778871/answer","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778871/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778871/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-10-27","Department for Exiting the European Union: Operating Costs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what estimate he has made of the cost to the public purse of running his Department between 23 June 2016 and 30 September 2017.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","110140"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778872","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-11-03","<p>The information requested is not held centrally therefore we are not in a position to provide this skills breakdown for particular groups of staff.</p><p>The Department for Exiting the European Union now has over 500 staff, and is growing fast. DExEU is drawing together expertise from a wide range of departments where there is specific relevant knowledge. The Department has sourced a large proportion of experienced staff from across Whitehall on a loan basis and a number of secondees from the private sector and the wider public sector. The Department obtains its legal advice from the Government Legal Department through a shared service arrangement.</p><p>We can confirm that at the time of your request we have a total of 15 staff on loan from the Ministry of Justice.</p><p>All departments are equipping themselves with the resources they need to get the best deal for the UK.</p><p> </p>","Wycombe","Mr Steve Baker",,"2017-11-03T14:42:27.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778872/answer","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778872/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778872/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-10-27","Department for Exiting the European Union: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, how many (a) legally qualified staff and (b) staff without legal qualifications currently working in his Department (i) have been transferred from and (ii) are on secondment from the Ministry of Justice.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","110138"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778873","Home Office","false","2017-11-01","<p>I refer the Hon. Lady to the answer given to the Hon. Member for Linlithgow and East Falkirk on 4 July 2017, UIN 1040.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-11-01T17:04:17.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778873/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778873/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778873/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-27","Migrant Workers: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether the Immigration Skills charge will be applied to employers of EU nationals that arrive after the grace period following the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Dr Philippa Whitford","Central Ayrshire","Dr Philippa Whitford","110040"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778874","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-06","<p>The fiscal impact of changes related to the UK leaving the EU will depend on the outcome of the negotiations.</p><p>The Government is clear that the UK’s future customs arrangements should be as frictionless as possible, ensuring that traffic continues to flow freely at all UK ports and airports, including Holyhead. HMRC is working with other government departments sharing responsibility for maintaining the flow of trade through our borders to mitigate the risk of delays relating to EU exit. HMRC has engaged with a large number of businesses, ports, airports and other organisations across the UK, including from Wales, to understand what may impact them in future and to support the smooth and orderly implementation of any new arrangements.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-11-06T12:13:50.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778874/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778874/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778874/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-10-27","Holyhead Port: Customs","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether the Government has made an estimate of the cost to the public purse of introducing customs checks at Holyhead Port; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Hywel Williams","Arfon","Hywel Williams","110051"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778023","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-11-06","<p>The UK Government continues to hold discussions with all parties in the dispute. The Prime Minister, Foreign Secretary and other ministers have all spoken to their counterparts, calling for a de-escalation, the lifting of the current restrictions, and encouraging them to get behind Kuwait’s mediation efforts. We have made clear that Gulf unity matters to the security and stability of the region.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-11-06T16:03:32.08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778023/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778023/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778023/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-10-26","Qatar: Diplomatic Relations","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, in the light of the severing of relations between Qatar and Saudi Arabia, Egypt, the United Arab Emirates and Bahrain in June, whether they have held discussions with the governments of those states about the possibility of resuming diplomatic relations; and if so, what was the outcome of those discussions.","false","Biography information for Lord Ahmed",,"Lord Ahmed","HL2569"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778024","The Senior Deputy Speaker","false","2017-11-02","<p>The Houses of Parliament do not receive a breakdown of waste by House so the figures and information below account for Estate wide totals.</p><p>(1) Since January 2012, Parliament has operated a mixed recycling scheme which captures paper, cardboard, plastics and cans as one waste stream and therefore we are not able to provide individual figures for paper collected as mixed recycling. Figures for mixed recycling (figures in kgs) are as follows:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>2017 (year to date)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>382,514</p></td><td><p>407,977</p></td><td><p>371,572</p></td><td><p>382,439</p></td><td><p>363,665</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>(2) Figures for general waste (figures in kgs) which is processed through an energy-from-waste facility are as follows:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>2017 (year to date)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>612,714</p></td><td><p>705,770</p></td><td><p>611,365</p></td><td><p>578,101</p></td><td><p>493,188</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Parliament’s food waste from catering facilities is sent to an anaerobic digestion facility and while this is not incinerated, the resulting bio gas produced by this process can be burned directly in a gas boiler to produce electricity. Figures for catering waste (figures in kgs) are as follows:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>2017 (year to date)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>160,973</p></td><td><p>194,474</p></td><td><p>136,285</p></td><td><p>195,082</p></td><td><p>180,755</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>(3) None of Parliament’s waste goes to landfill.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord McFall of Alcluith",,"2017-11-02T12:25:24.783Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778024/answer","Biography information for Lord McFall of Alcluith","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778024/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778024/answer",,,,,"204",,"Senior Deputy Speaker (HoL)","2017-10-26","House of Lords: Waste Management","2","House of Lords","To ask the Senior Deputy Speaker what quantity of (1) paper for recycling, (2) waste for incineration, and (3) residual refuse, was collected within the House of Lords in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Lord Greaves",,"Lord Greaves","HL2570"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778025","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-11-08","<p>Bacteria naturally adapt and find new ways to survive the effects of an antibiotic; any use of an antibiotic accelerates the risk that bacteria will develop resistance. In its response last year to the Independent Review on Antimicrobial Resistance, the Government set a target to reduce antibiotic use by 20% across all food-producing species from 2014 baseline data to 50mg/kg by 2018. Latest data show that antibiotic use in 2016 was 45 mg/kg. Defra also undertook to work with the livestock industry to set sector-specific targets for reducing antibiotic use by the end of this year. These targets have now been published which can be found here: <a href="http://www.ruma.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/RUMA-Targets-Task-Force-Report-2017-FINAL.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.ruma.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/RUMA-Targets-Task-Force-Report-2017-FINAL.pdf</a></p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2017-11-08T13:32:06.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778025/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778025/answer","RUMA - Targets Task Force Report 2017.pdf","RUMA - Targets Task Force Report 2017.pdf","RUMA - Targets Task Force Report 2017","RUMA - Targets Task Force Report 2017","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778025/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-10-26","Livestock: Antibiotics","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what is their assessment of the contribution of animal farming in the UK to the growing resistance to antibiotics; and whether they have set targets for the reduction of antibiotics use in animal farming.","false","Biography information for Lord Greaves",,"Lord Greaves","HL2571"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778026","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-11-07","<p>The Government believes that both conventional and organic farming offers opportunities for expansion and increased penetration of the domestic and overseas markets.</p><p> </p><p>The Government recognises that organic farming and food can make a significant contribution helping to achieve environmental objectives, together with the additional consumer choice it offers, and supports this in England through the provision of financial aid for both conversion to and maintenance of organic status.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2017-11-07T15:10:37.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778026/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778026/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778026/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-10-26","Organic Farming","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether it is their policy to encourage organic farming and to increase the amount of land used by that sector; and if so, what actions they are taking in support of that policy.","false","Biography information for Lord Greaves",,"Lord Greaves","HL2572"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778027","Department for Education","false","2017-11-09","<p>The Government is not responsible for deciding which courses further education institutions deliver. This is the responsibility of the institutions themselves who will take account of Government priorities as well as skills demands identified by local stakeholders and employers.</p><p> </p><p>As part of our reforms to technical education, we are establishing a common framework of 15 technical education routes that encompass all employment-based and college-based training. The implementation of the routes will be phased, and the Agriculture, Environment and Animal Care route will be rolled out in September 2022. Within the routes will sit new T level qualifications. As with all the routes, the content of T levels within the Agriculture, Environment and Animal Care route will be determined by advisory groups of employers, professionals and practitioners.</p><p> </p><p>On 11 October the government published a T level Action Plan, which set out progress on the technical education reforms. Later this year, the Government will hold a public consultation on the new T level qualifications.</p>",,"Lord Agnew of Oulton",,"2017-11-09T14:52:40.97Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778027/answer","Biography information for Lord Agnew of Oulton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778027/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778027/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-10-26","Agriculture: Education","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they intend to expand the provision of courses in organic and agroecological practices in agricultural colleges and other appropriate institutions.","false","Biography information for Lord Greaves",,"Lord Greaves","HL2573"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778028","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-11-09","<p>It has been the practice of successive Governments not to comment on legal advice that may or may not have been received. A clear majority of the electorate voted to leave the EU and we will respect the will of the British people. As a matter of firm policy, our notification will not be withdrawn, for the simple reason that people voted to leave. And we are determined to see through that instruction.</p>",,"Lord Callanan",,"2017-11-09T13:33:43.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778028/answer","Biography information for Lord Callanan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778028/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778028/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-10-26","Brexit","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they have taken legal advice on whether they can revoke or pause the Article 50 two year timetable.","false","Biography information for Lord Myners",,"Lord Myners","HL2574"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778029","Department for Transport","false","2017-11-03","<p>The Government has set out its preferred option for an additional runway in the South East, which will be required by 2030. However through the recent Aviation Strategy Call for Evidence the government has consulted on the proposal to support airports throughout the UK making the best use of their existing runways, subject to environmental issues being addressed and will respond in due course.</p><p> </p><p>Beyond this, a new Aviation Strategy will consider whether there is a need for a new framework to be developed to allow airports to grow sustainably, and if so what that framework should look like.</p>",,"Baroness Sugg",,"2017-11-03T11:07:12.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778029/answer","Biography information for Baroness Sugg","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778029/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778029/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-10-26","London Airports","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, further to the Written Statement by Lord Callanan on 24 October (HLWS196), whether they intend to publish a new critical path showing how they will address congestion at the five London airports.","false","Biography information for Lord Spicer",,"Lord Spicer","HL2575"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778030","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-11-09","<p>Under the European Regional Development Fund (ERDF) 2014–20 Programme in England, the funding available has been allocated to Local Enterprise Partnership (LEP) areas and it is then for these partners to inform central Government when and where investments in their respective areas take place. The ERDF is the main source of EU funding used to support infrastructure in localities. This is complemented by the European Social Fund (ESF) which is also allocated to LEP areas in England and supports employment, skills and social inclusion.</p><p>The level of EU Structural Funds (the combination of the ERDF and the ESF) that has been allocated to each LEP area, including Cornwall and the Isles of Scilly, Heart of the South West and England can be found (attached) here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/eu-structural-funds-uk-allocations-2014-to-2020" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/eu-structural-funds-uk-allocations-2014-to-2020</a>.</p><p>The Cornwall and Isles of Scilly LEP area allocation is significantly greater than that of the Heart of the South West. This is because the EU categorises Cornwall and the Isles of Scilly as ‘a Less Developed Region’ whereas it categorises Heart of the South West as ‘a More Developed Region’. These categories are assigned according to the per capita gross domestic product (GDP) of each of these areas.</p><p>Details of population by LEP area from 2010 onwards using the Nomis Database which can be found here: <a href="https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/reports/lmp/lep/contents.aspx" target="_blank">https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/reports/lmp/lep/contents.aspx</a></p><p>Details of projects that have been funded are available (attached) on GOV.UK: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/european-structural-and-investment-funds-useful-resources" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/european-structural-and-investment-funds-useful-resources</a></p><p>The government has committed to develop the UK Shared Prosperity Fund as a successor to EU structural fund programmes. This new Fund affords a fresh opportunity to spend money according to our own priorities, improve productivity and reduce economic inequality across the country.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","HL2577","2017-11-09T14:08:44.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778030/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778030/answer","171108 ERDF HL2577 2576.pdf ; 171108 EUstructural-funds-uk-allocations-2014-to-2020- HL2577 HL2576.pdf","171108 ERDF HL2577 2576.pdf ; 171108 EUstructural-funds-uk-allocations-2014-to-2020- HL2577 HL2576.pdf","ERDF ; EU Structural Fund","ERDF ; EU Structural Fund","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778030/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-26","European Regional Development Fund","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what was the value of European Regional Development Fund support payments per capita in real terms in (1) Cornwall, (2) Devon, and (3) England, in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Goss Moor",,"Lord Taylor of Goss Moor","HL2576"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778031","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-11-09","<p>Under the European Regional Development Fund (ERDF) 2014–20 Programme in England, the funding available has been allocated to Local Enterprise Partnership (LEP) areas and it is then for these partners to inform central Government when and where investments in their respective areas take place. The ERDF is the main source of EU funding used to support infrastructure in localities. This is complemented by the European Social Fund (ESF) which is also allocated to LEP areas in England and supports employment, skills and social inclusion.</p><p>The level of EU Structural Funds (the combination of the ERDF and the ESF) that has been allocated to each LEP area, including Cornwall and the Isles of Scilly, Heart of the South West and England can be found (attached) here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/eu-structural-funds-uk-allocations-2014-to-2020" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/eu-structural-funds-uk-allocations-2014-to-2020</a>.</p><p>The Cornwall and Isles of Scilly LEP area allocation is significantly greater than that of the Heart of the South West. This is because the EU categorises Cornwall and the Isles of Scilly as ‘a Less Developed Region’ whereas it categorises Heart of the South West as ‘a More Developed Region’. These categories are assigned according to the per capita gross domestic product (GDP) of each of these areas.</p><p>Details of population by LEP area from 2010 onwards using the Nomis Database which can be found here: <a href="https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/reports/lmp/lep/contents.aspx" target="_blank">https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/reports/lmp/lep/contents.aspx</a></p><p>Details of projects that have been funded are available (attached) on GOV.UK: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/european-structural-and-investment-funds-useful-resources" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/european-structural-and-investment-funds-useful-resources</a></p><p>The government has committed to develop the UK Shared Prosperity Fund as a successor to EU structural fund programmes. This new Fund affords a fresh opportunity to spend money according to our own priorities, improve productivity and reduce economic inequality across the country.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","HL2576","2017-11-09T14:08:44.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778031/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778031/answer","171108 ERDF HL2577 2576.pdf ; 171108 EUstructural-funds-uk-allocations-2014-to-2020- HL2577 HL2576.pdf","171108 ERDF HL2577 2576.pdf ; 171108 EUstructural-funds-uk-allocations-2014-to-2020- HL2577 HL2576.pdf","ERDF ; EU Structural Fund","ERDF ; EU Structural Fund","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778031/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-26","Infrastructure: EU Grants and Loans","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what was the value of EU infrastructure support payments per capita in real terms in (1) Cornwall, (2) Devon, and (3) England, in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Goss Moor",,"Lord Taylor of Goss Moor","HL2577"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778032","Department for Transport","false","2017-11-07","<p>The information in the attached table shows the Department for Transport’s total final funding contributions to local major transport projects in England approved since 2014 following consideration of final business cases. Other projects in the programme are still in development. The current programme totals £2.6bn of which £1.66bn is being provided by the Department. This is in addition to the significant investment we are making to improve local transport through other funding streams, including local highways maintenance and integrated transport funding.</p>",,"Baroness Sugg",,"2017-11-07T12:04:06.89Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778032/answer","Biography information for Baroness Sugg","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778032/answer","HL2578 - DfT's Funding Contribution to Local Major Transport Projects.xlsx","HL2578 - DfT's Funding Contribution to Local Major Transport Projects.xlsx","HL2578 - Table with DfT's contributions","HL2578 - Table with DfT's contributions","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778032/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-10-26","Transport: Finance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what projects have been awarded funding through the local major transport projects fund since 2014; what was the amount of funding awarded for each project; and what was the purpose of each project.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Goss Moor",,"Lord Taylor of Goss Moor","HL2578"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778033","Department for Transport","false","2017-11-07","<p>The Government is still considering the business case for the A30 to St Austell Link Road scheme and will announce a funding decision in due course.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Sugg",,"2017-11-07T12:03:15.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778033/answer","Biography information for Baroness Sugg","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778033/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778033/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-10-26","A30","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government when they plan to make a decision on the outline business case to fund the A30 to St Austell link road.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Goss Moor",,"Lord Taylor of Goss Moor","HL2579"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778034","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-11-06","<p>Data on the amount raised by councils under the empty homes premium is not collected by the Department.</p><p>The average house price in England is published by the Land Registry in conjunction with the Office for National Statistics, and can be found (attached) at the following link</p><p>http://landregistry.data.gov.uk/app/ukhpi?utm_medium=GOV.UK&amp;utm_source=datadownload&amp;utm_campaign=tool&amp;utm_term=9.30_11_04_17</p><p>Billing authorities already have discretion to impose a premium of up to 50 per cent on the council tax due on long-term empty properties, and there are no current plans to review that arrangement. The Department has not made any comparative assessment of the amounts raised under the premium and house price rises.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2017-11-06T16:12:20.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778034/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778034/answer","171031 House Price Index HL2580.pdf","171031 House Price Index HL2580.pdf","House price index","House price index","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778034/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-26","Council Tax: Empty Property","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what is their estimate of the amount raised by councils in England under the empty home premium in each year since its introduction; what was the average house price in England in each of those years; what comparative assessment they have made of the amounts raised under the premium and house price rises; and whether they intend to review the maximum amount that councils in England may charge.","false","Biography information for Lord Beecham",,"Lord Beecham","HL2580"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778035","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-11-03","<p>The Government’s intention is to maintain current organic legislation in the EU (Withdrawal) Bill which will convert the existing body of EU environmental and farming regulations into UK law. This Government has made clear that we intend to retain our existing standards once we have left the EU. Maintaining the legislation ensures continuity of production and trade for our organic operators.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2017-11-03T12:12:12.81Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778035/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778035/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778035/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-10-26","Organic Farming","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether, following the UK's withdrawal from the EU, they intend to maintain or amend the legal framework regulating organic farming.","false","Biography information for Lord Greaves",,"Lord Greaves","HL2581"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778036","Home Office","false","2017-11-09","<p>The letter of 25<sup>th</sup> July has been responded to. However, a response to further representations from the Hong Kong Police Association is being drafted and will be released in due course.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-11-09T16:14:16.29Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778036/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778036/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778036/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-26","Police: Hong Kong","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what was their response to the representations made by the Royal Hong Kong Police Association in its letter of 25 July to the Home Secretary.","false","Biography information for Lord Goodlad",,"Lord Goodlad","HL2582"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778037","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-11-09","<p>The table below displays the number of offenders managed by an MTC Novo Provider (London Community Rehabilitation Company and Thames Valley Community Rehabilitation Company) with an absence recorded on nDelius (the national case management system for Probation) during the period of 1 April 2017 to 30 June 2017. This data is not limited to contact with Probation Officers and includes all categories of enforceable contacts, including Unpaid Work, Accredited Programmes and other interventions.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>Thames Valley CRC</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>London CRC</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>All MTC Novo</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Acceptable Absence</p></td><td><p>2,624</p></td><td><p>10,584</p></td><td><p><strong>13,208</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Unacceptable Absence</p></td><td><p>1,405</p></td><td><p>10,680</p></td><td><p><strong>12,085</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Attendance Not Recorded</p></td><td><p>776</p></td><td><p>1,785</p></td><td><p><strong>2,561</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total Offenders managed</strong></p></td><td><p>4,133</p></td><td><p>23,248</p></td><td><p><strong>27,381</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p>Absences are categorised as Acceptable or Unacceptable. Acceptable absences include contacts that have been cancelled for administrative reasons (for example, 15 days of Unpaid Work, which is typical for a 100 hours order, originally booked to be worked on a Thursday but later changed to a Wednesday to reflect childcare arrangements for an offender would count as 15 Acceptable Absences), as well as circumstances where an offender has provided good reasons for their failure to attend (for example, a letter from a GP to prove ill health).</p><p> </p><p>Our policy is clear that offenders who fail to comply more than once with their order (without an acceptable explanation), should be subject to breach proceedings. We enforce this requirement robustly with all providers of Probation services.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2017-11-09T13:29:58.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778037/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778037/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778037/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-26","MTCnovo","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how many offenders have failed to keep appointments with probation officers employed by MTC Novo.","false","Biography information for Lord Laming",,"Lord Laming","HL2583"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778038","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-11-09","<p>The sentencing framework already gives courts the flexibility to select community order requirements which are a robust alternative to custody, and are tailored to address the specific issues that contribute to reoffending. We are committed to ensuring that community penalties are tough, effective and command the confidence of sentencers, and are continuing to explore further improvements that could be made to probation services.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2017-11-09T13:30:26.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778038/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778038/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778038/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-26","Alternatives to Prison","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what action they are taking to ensure that the courts have robust and reliable non-custodial sentences available to them.","false","Biography information for Lord Laming",,"Lord Laming","HL2584"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778039","Department for International Development","false","2017-11-08","<p>The Central African Pension Fund will next be officially valued in July 2018. It is for Crown Agents, as Trustees of the Fund, to consider how to respond to any deficit.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2017-11-08T14:07:02.727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778039/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778039/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778039/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-10-26","Central African Pension Fund","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon on 25 October (HL1890), whether they intend to make good the deficit in the Central African Pension Fund, as they did in 2010.","false","Biography information for Lord Goodlad",,"Lord Goodlad","HL2585"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778040","Cabinet Office","false","2017-11-09","<p>The Government only holds this information from 2011. The majority of spend is conducted on a network (national) basis and splitting this spend by region is not possible.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>TV</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Radio</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>£33,379,859</p></td><td><p>£9,186,954</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>£48,351,924</p></td><td><p>£15,243,673</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>£39,254,363</p></td><td><p>£17,577,155</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>£32,729,643</p></td><td><p>£14,308,621</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>£51,729,850</p></td><td><p>£18,884,897</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>£48,669,686</p></td><td><p>£11,927,962</p></td></tr></tbody></table>",,"Lord Young of Cookham",,"2017-11-09T16:06:55.26Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778040/answer","Biography information for Lord Young of Cookham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778040/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778040/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-10-26","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport: Advertising","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how much they and their agencies spent on commercial advertising on (1) TV, and (2) radio, in each year since 2009, broken down by region.","false","Biography information for Baroness Smith of Basildon",,"Baroness Smith of Basildon","HL2586"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778041","Cabinet Office","false","2017-11-06","<p>None. The conduct of the boundary review is a matter for the four independent and impartial Boundary Commissions.</p>",,"Lord Young of Cookham",,"2017-11-06T12:41:05.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778041/answer","Biography information for Lord Young of Cookham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778041/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778041/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-10-26","Constituencies","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the effectiveness of advertising the boundary commission consultations on commercial radio.","false","Biography information for Baroness Smith of Basildon",,"Baroness Smith of Basildon","HL2587"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778042","Department for International Development","false","2017-11-08","<p>Our deepest sympathies are with the people of Sierra Leone affected by the mudslide and flooding. The UK allocated £5m for emergency power and clean water, and to clear waterways to prevent further flooding.</p><p>Since Ebola, DFID has provided clean water and sanitation to over 500,000 people, including through new boreholes across Freetown. We are upgrading power supplies and doubling the number of households with access to solar energy. This support includes technical training for local workers, which will improve their ability to respond in times of crisis. The World Bank and UN are assisting the government to develop a long term strategy for urban planning, and we are working closely with them to assess the city’s longer term housing needs.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2017-11-08T14:13:03.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778042/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778042/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778042/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-10-26","Sierra Leone: Floods","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what measures they are taking to support the funding and planning of the infrastructure of Freetown following the flooding in August; and whether they intend to provide support for a programme to train technical experts.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Chesterton",,"Lord Hunt of Chesterton","HL2588"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778043","Department for International Development","false","2017-11-07","<p>The UK is deeply committed to the vital issues that UNESCO works on. But we have been crystal clear that we expect serious reform from UNESCO as an organisation. The 2016 Multilateral Development Review scored UNESCO lowest of all the agencies. This is not good enough. We will relentlessly keep up the pressure to drive up performance – and in particular to address serious concerns about financial and risk management.</p><p>The US’s relationship with UNESCO is a matter for them.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2017-11-07T13:41:10.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778043/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778043/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778043/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-10-26","UNESCO","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what is their policy for the prioritisation and funding of the future programmes of UNESCO, in the light of the decision of the United States to terminate its membership; and whether they will urge the United States to rejoin.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Chesterton",,"Lord Hunt of Chesterton","HL2589"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778044","Department of Health","false","2017-11-07","<p>The UK Antimicrobial Resistance (AMR) Strategy published in 2013 set out the key actions needed to tackle AMR: preventing infections, making appropriate use of the treatments available, and promoting the development of new treatments. In 2016 the government announced ambitions to halve healthcare-associated Gram-negative bloodstream infections and inappropriate prescribing of antimicrobials by 2020-2021. To promote the development of new drugs, diagnostics and alternative treatments we have established unprecedented levels of research collaboration, together with increased investment, including the £50 million Global AMR Innovation Fund. The Government is committed to working with the global finance and health community to develop a global system that rewards companies that develop new, successful antibiotics and make them available to all who need them.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2017-11-07T16:14:16.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778044/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778044/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778044/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-10-26","Antimicrobials: Drug Resistance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how cures and treatments in the NHS are being developed to reduce the danger in hospitals of anti-microbial resistance.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Chesterton",,"Lord Hunt of Chesterton","HL2590"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778045","Home Office","false","2017-11-06","<p>The Post Office currently provides the distribution service for Biometric Residence Permits (BRP).</p><p> </p><p>There are 199 Post Offices across England, Scotland Wales and N Ireland providing the collection service to overseas Applicants.</p><p> </p><p>There are no plans to expand this service.</p><p> </p><p>For those applicants who apply in country for a BRP the card is delivered using a secure courier service.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-11-06T18:00:08.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778045/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778045/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778045/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-26","Biometric Residence Permits","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what plans they have to extend the distribution network for biometric residence permits.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Chesterton",,"Lord Hunt of Chesterton","HL2591"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778046","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-11-09","<p>Our priority is to prevent or reduce waste in the first place – keeping packaging produced to the minimum of protecting the product and communicating with the consumer. Our Packaging (Essential Requirements) Regulations require businesses to ensure that all their packaging does not exceed what is needed to make sure that the products are safe, hygienic and acceptable for both the packed product and for the consumer. These Regulations apply to those responsible for the packing or filling of products into packaging and those importing packed or filled packaging into the UK from elsewhere.</p><p> </p><p>In September 2016, the Waste and Resources Action Programme (WRAP) and an industry advisory group published a framework for greater consistency encouraging councils to recycle a common set of materials, as well as setting out actions to rationalise packaging, particularly plastics, into items that can be collected for recycling while supporting innovation in packaging design.</p><p> </p><p>Officials regularly meet with businesses and retailers to discuss a range of issues related to the recyclability of packaging. There will also be further opportunities for dialogue between officials and industry to inform the development of the new Resources and Waste Strategy.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble","HL2593","2017-11-09T16:45:41.333Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778046/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778046/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778046/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-10-26","Packaging: Waste","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what action they have taken in the last six months to encourage best practice in terms of limiting packaging waste by major retailers; and what action they are planning to take in the next six months.","false","Biography information for Lord Hayward",,"Lord Hayward","HL2592"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778047","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-11-09","<p>Our priority is to prevent or reduce waste in the first place – keeping packaging produced to the minimum of protecting the product and communicating with the consumer. Our Packaging (Essential Requirements) Regulations require businesses to ensure that all their packaging does not exceed what is needed to make sure that the products are safe, hygienic and acceptable for both the packed product and for the consumer. These Regulations apply to those responsible for the packing or filling of products into packaging and those importing packed or filled packaging into the UK from elsewhere.</p><p> </p><p>In September 2016, the Waste and Resources Action Programme (WRAP) and an industry advisory group published a framework for greater consistency encouraging councils to recycle a common set of materials, as well as setting out actions to rationalise packaging, particularly plastics, into items that can be collected for recycling while supporting innovation in packaging design.</p><p> </p><p>Officials regularly meet with businesses and retailers to discuss a range of issues related to the recyclability of packaging. There will also be further opportunities for dialogue between officials and industry to inform the development of the new Resources and Waste Strategy.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble","HL2592","2017-11-09T16:45:41.383Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778047/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778047/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778047/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-10-26","Packaging: Waste","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what meetings they have held in the last six months with major retailers to encourage best practice in terms of limiting packaging waste; what responses they received; and what further meetings are planned for the next six months.","false","Biography information for Lord Hayward",,"Lord Hayward","HL2593"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778048","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-11-09","<p>The Government has not taken any direct steps to encourage greater use of IT solutions as an alternative to packaging promotions.</p><p> </p><p>Buy-one-get-one-free deals represent a small proportion of supermarket promotions, and increasingly retailers are moving to more ‘everyday low pricing’ models or temporary price reductions. The Government has worked through the Waste and Resources Action Programme (WRAP) to encourage retailers to provide alternative promotions for perishable food. If volume-based promotions are used (e.g. ‘3 for the price of 2’), then retailers should provide advice on how to store or freeze these foods to ensure that they are used and not wasted. This approach enables consumers to make savings but still buy the amounts or range of food that is right for them.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2017-11-09T16:35:12.097Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778048/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778048/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778048/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-10-26","Packaging: Waste","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what steps they have taken, and are planning to take, to discourage the use of packaging to promote multi-purchase discounts, and to encourage greater use of IT solutions as an alternative.","false","Biography information for Lord Hayward",,"Lord Hayward","HL2594"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778049","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-11-06","<p>There has been no formal review of the policy, but since the introduction of the Single Use Carrier Bags charges (England) Order 2015, 9 billion fewer single use carrier bags have been used and £95 million raised for good causes by retailers. This Order is due for review by October 2020.</p><p> </p><p>Any decision to review the wider policy ahead of that date would be done within the context of the Government’s forthcoming Waste and Resources Strategy.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2017-11-06T17:59:15.6Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778049/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778049/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778049/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-10-26","Plastic Bags","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they have recently reviewed their policy in relation to minimising further the use of plastic bags within retailing; and if not, whether they intend to review that policy in the next six months.","false","Biography information for Lord Hayward",,"Lord Hayward","HL2595"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778050","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-11-09","<p>It has been the practice of successive Governments not to comment on legal advice that may or may not have been received. A clear majority of the electorate voted to leave the EU and we will respect the will of the British people. As a matter of firm policy, our notification will not be withdrawn, for the simple reason that people voted to leave. And we are determined to see through that instruction.</p>",,"Lord Callanan",,"2017-11-09T13:35:26.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778050/answer","Biography information for Lord Callanan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778050/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778050/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-10-26","Brexit","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Anelay of St Johns on 23 October (HL2086) concerning constitutional advice on the possible revocation of the Article 50 notice, whether they will now answer the question asked.","false","Biography information for Lord Smith of Finsbury",,"Lord Smith of Finsbury","HL2596"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778051","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-11-09","<p>Under the prudential system, local authorities in England are free to borrow without government consent, providing that their borrowing is affordable. When calculating an affordable level of borrowing, local authorities are required by statute to have regard to the Prudential Code issued by the Chartered Institute of Public Finance and Accountancy. Borrowing in the Housing Revenue Account can be used to fund the delivery of new social housing. This borrowing is capped, but there remains unused borrowing headroom of £3.5 billion (up from £2.9bn in 2012).</p><p>The measure used in the Government fiscal mandate to measure the national debt is Public Sector Net Debt excluding public sector banks (PSND). This covers all institutions classified to the public sector by the Office for National Statistics apart from RBS and is produced on a consolidated basis. As part of the public sector, local authorities borrowing will therefore increase PSND.</p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2017-11-09T14:06:40.423Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778051/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778051/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778051/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-26","Local Government: Borrowing","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether local authorities are free to borrow against the security of their capital assets, for example for new housing; if so, whether such borrowing is treated as increasing the national debt; and if so, why.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL2597"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778052","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-11-09","<p>Muslims are free to enter into a legally valid marriage in their place of worship under the same provisions that apply to most other religious groups. The Government recognises that there are complex reasons that some do not, including conscious choice. We are considering the issues, but we have not seen evidence that changing the law would necessarily address the concern.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2017-11-09T13:30:51.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778052/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778052/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778052/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-26","Marriage: Muslims","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they have any plans to ask the Law Commission to examine how to improve the protection of British Muslim women in marriage law.","false","Biography information for Lord Lester of Herne Hill",,"Lord Lester of Herne Hill","HL2598"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778053","Department of Health","false","2017-11-07","<p>Data on the number of English patients on the methadone treatment programme is not collected in the format requested.</p><p> </p><p>Information on the cost of local drug treatment programmes is not collected centrally.</p><p> </p><p>Deaths where methadone was among the substances mentioned on the death certificate are published by Office for National Statistics for residents of England and Wales for each calendar year, based on deaths registered in the year. These were 220 in 2005, 355 in 2010,and 434 in 2015.</p><p> </p><p>The <em>Adult substance misuse statistics from the National Drug Treatment Monitoring System</em> <em>(NDTMS) 2015-16</em> report shows that 39% of opiate users who were reviewed after six months of treatment had not used opiates in the previous four weeks. Of those who reported that they were injecting at the start of treatment, 55% reported not injecting in the previous four weeks when reviewed after six months. This data is not available in a comparable form for previous years. A copy of the report is attached.</p><p> </p><p>It should be noted that these are not outcomes for every opiate user in treatment, but specifically for those reviewed at six months within that year, and that not all opiate users are injecting.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2017-11-07T16:09:50.747Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778053/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778053/answer","Adult substance misuse statistics from the National Drug Treatment Monitoring System (NDTMS) 2015-16.pdf","Adult substance misuse statistics from the National Drug Treatment Monitoring System (NDTMS) 2015-16.pdf","Adult substance misuse statistics","Adult substance misuse statistics","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778053/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-10-26","Methadone","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how many English patients were on the methadone treatment programme in (1) 2005, (2) 2010, and (3) 2015; in each of those years (a) what was the cost of the programme, (b) how many deaths from methadone abuse, whether of those on the programme or not, were recorded, and (c) how many patients on the programme ceased injecting behaviour and the use of other illicit drugs.","false","Biography information for Lord Brooke of Alverthorpe",,"Lord Brooke of Alverthorpe","HL2599"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778054","Department of Health","false","2017-11-07","<p>The Government has not made any assessment of methadone prescribing as a drug treatment in isolation. The National Institute for Health and Clinical Excellence has published several pieces of guidance on drug treatment. They recommend opioid substitute treatment with either methadone or buprenorphine, delivered alongside psychosocial treatments, as the frontline treatment for opioid (heroin) dependency. This is the treatment with the strongest international evidence base.</p><p>The prescribing of methadone, or any other opioid substitute therapy, only starts after an assessment by a competent clinician, in conjunction with the patient and taking into account their needs and supported by local clinical governance arrangements.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2017-11-07T16:07:57.513Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778054/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778054/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778054/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-10-26","Methadone","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what is their assessment of the effectiveness of the methadone prescribing treatment as a means to achieving a drug free lifestyle.","false","Biography information for Lord Brooke of Alverthorpe",,"Lord Brooke of Alverthorpe","HL2600"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778055","Cabinet Office","false","2017-11-09","<p>On appointment to each new office, Ministers provide a list of all relevant interests to their Permanent Secretary, which are considered by the Cabinet Office, and the Prime Minister’s Independent Adviser on Ministers’ Interests.</p>",,"Lord Young of Cookham",,"2017-11-09T16:09:15.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778055/answer","Biography information for Lord Young of Cookham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778055/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778055/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-10-26","Department for Education: Ministers","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they carry out due diligence into the commercial activities in the education sector of prospective ministerial appointments in the Department for Education before making such appointments.","false","Biography information for Lord Foulkes of Cumnock",,"Lord Foulkes of Cumnock","HL2601"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778056","Cabinet Office","false","2017-11-09","<p>The Department is not aware of having given any financial, organisational or other support to the Policy Exchange in the last five years.</p>",,"Lord Young of Cookham",,"2017-11-09T16:07:46.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778056/answer","Biography information for Lord Young of Cookham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778056/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778056/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-10-26","Policy Exchange","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they have given any financial, organisational or other support to the Policy Exchange in the last five years; and if so, what was the source of that support.","false","Biography information for Lord Foulkes of Cumnock",,"Lord Foulkes of Cumnock","HL2602"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778057","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-11-03","<p>We are committed to working closely with the Scottish Government and the other devolved administrations to develop a future fishing policy that works for the whole of the UK. We will respect the devolution settlements and envisage that the powers of the devolved administrations will increase as we leave the EU.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>There have been extensive discussions at Ministerial and official level between Defra and the devolved administrations, including the Scottish Government.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>As part of this regular engagement, the Environment Secretary met the devolved administrations in September and will meet them again on 6 November.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2017-11-03T11:38:25.367Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778057/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778057/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778057/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-10-26","Fisheries: Scotland","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they have had discussions with the Scottish Government with a view to agreeing a joint policy on fisheries in advance of the time when the UK leaves the EU and withdraws from the London Fisheries Convention.","false","Biography information for Lord MacKenzie of Culkein",,"Lord MacKenzie of Culkein","HL2603"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778058","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-11-07","<p>Defra is making a full assessment of the scale and volume of sea-based patrol capability required after we leave the EU with the Marine Management Organisation (MMO), Ministry of Defence, Royal Navy and other agencies.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has established a Joint Maritime Operational Coordination Centre to coordinate all sea-based patrol activity across marine agencies to derive maximum surveillance benefit.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2017-11-07T15:45:19.853Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778058/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778058/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778058/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-10-26","Navy: Fisheries","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the case for additional naval assets to provide for increased protection to UK fisheries in both the UK territorial waters and the Exclusive Economic Zone following withdrawal from the EU and the London Fisheries Convention.","false","Biography information for Lord MacKenzie of Culkein",,"Lord MacKenzie of Culkein","HL2604"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778059","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-11-03","<p>The UK Government has had no discussions with the government of Denmark about the London Fisheries Convention or Danish claims to have historical rights to fish in UK waters. Denmark does not have rights within the UK’s 6-12 mile zone which is the area covered under the London Convention, but does have access to the UK’s 12-200 nautical mile exclusive economic zone under the Common Fisheries Policy. The Government has been clear that when we leave the EU, the UK will be an Independent Coastal State and will be able to decide on access to UK waters.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2017-11-03T12:29:25.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778059/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778059/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778059/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-10-26","Fisheries: Denmark","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they have had discussions with the government of Denmark following the decision to withdraw the UK from the London Fisheries Convention and the Danish claim to have historical rights to fish in UK waters that precede the signing of the Convention.","false","Biography information for Lord MacKenzie of Culkein",,"Lord MacKenzie of Culkein","HL2605"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778060","Home Office","false","2017-11-07","<p>The HMPO Parliamentary Liaison team merged with the UK Visas and Immigration MP Account Management team on 3 April. The MP Account Management team answers enquiries from Members of Parliament and Members of the House of Lords. The HMPO Parliamentary Liaison line closed on 18 April. Members of the House of Lords can contact their regional MP Account Management team for all passport related enquiries.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-11-07T16:14:34.15Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778060/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778060/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778060/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-26","HM Passport Office","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government why HM Passport Office (HMPO) has withdrawn the Parliamentary Liaison Team function and discontinued the designated parliamentary helpline; and why the recorded message from HMPO on the discontinued advice and assistance helpline gives some advice for future contacts in respect of Members of the House of Commons but does not do so for members of the House of Lords.","false","Biography information for Lord MacKenzie of Culkein",,"Lord MacKenzie of Culkein","HL2606"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778061","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-11-02","<p>Hinkley Point C is scheduled to come online from 2025 with an electricity generating capacity of 3.2 GW. This represents 7% of the UK’s electricity needs based on estimated demand in the period 2025-2030.</p><p>The Contract for Difference (CfD), agreed in September 2016, is an agreement for the Low Carbon Contracts Company Limited (LCCC) on behalf of electricity bill-payers to pay the generator the difference between the wholesale market price and a ‘strike price’ for every megawatt hour of electricity that it generates.</p><p>The payments under the Hinkley Point C CfD will depend on wholesale prices at the time. In our published 2016 HPC value-for-money assessment, it was shown using a central scenario based on 2016 prices that the support payments in the first three years of the plant’s operation from 2025 are expected to be approximately £590m, £860m and £860m respectively (2012 prices, undiscounted).</p><p>The difference payments under the CfD are only one element of a consumer's electricity bill, which will also include the wholesale price of electricity. A fall in the wholesale price would result in an increase in top-up payments, and conversely an increase in the wholesale price would result in a fall in top up payments, and payments by the generator to the LCCC should the wholesale price rise above the strike price. The overall price paid for electricity generated by HPC is therefore fixed at the strike price for the contract term of 35 years, after which the difference payments will stop.</p>",,"Lord Henley",,"2017-11-02T16:14:58.523Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778061/answer","Biography information for Lord Henley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778061/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778061/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-10-26","Hinkley Point C Power Station","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government when the Hinkley Point C nuclear power station is due to come on stream; what its output rate will be; what is the estimated total subsidy per year for each of the first three years of operation; and who will pay that subsidy.","false","Biography information for Lord Marlesford",,"Lord Marlesford","HL2607"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778062","Home Office","false","2017-11-06","<p>For the purposes of your question, I have assumed that by ‘acts of terrorism’ you refer to terrorist attacks (declared as such by the Police). During the past five years, there have been 8 such terrorist attacks within England and Wales, which have claimed 39 lives (plus five perpetrators). There have been no instances where the perpetrator(s) claimed to be acting ‘in the name of Islam’, however, in four of the eight attacks, Daesh claimed that the perpetrator(s) was or were one of its activists or soldiers.</p><p>Please see the below table for a breakdown of these figures.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Date</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Terrorist Attack</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Number of people who lost their lives</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Did Daesh claim that the perpetrator was one of its activists or soldiers</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>15 Sept 2017</p></td><td><p>Parson’s Green Underground attack</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>Yes</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>19 June 2017</p></td><td><p>Finsbury Park Mosque attack</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>No</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>3 June 2017</p></td><td><p>London Bridge / Borough Market attack</p></td><td><p>8</p></td><td><p>Yes</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>22 May 2017</p></td><td><p>Manchester Arena attack</p></td><td><p>22</p></td><td><p>Yes</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>22 March 2017</p></td><td><p>Westminster Bridge / Palace of Westminster attack</p></td><td><p>5</p></td><td><p>Yes</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>16 June 2016</p></td><td><p>The murder of Jo Cox</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>No</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>22 May 2013</p></td><td><p>The murder of Lee Rigby</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>No</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>29 April 2013</p></td><td><p>The murder of Mohammed Saleem</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>No</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Total: 39 victims</p></td><td><p><strong> </strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-11-06T17:58:29.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778062/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778062/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778062/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-26","Terrorism","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what acts of terrorism occured in England and Wales in each of the last five years; and in each case (1) how many people lost their lives, and (2) whether (a) the perpetrator claimed to be acting in the name of Islam, and (b) the Islamic State claimed that the perpetrator was one of its activists or soldiers.","false","Biography information for Lord Marlesford",,"Lord Marlesford","HL2608"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778063","Home Office","false","2017-11-06","<p>Approximately 850 UK linked individuals of national security concern have travelled to engage with the Syrian conflict. We estimate that just under half have returned and approximately 15% are now dead. This number includes all those of national security concern, not just those affiliated with Daesh. Everyone who returns from taking part in the conflict in Syria or Iraq must expect to be investigated by the police to determine if they have committed criminal offences, and to ensure that they do not pose a threat to our national security. In addition to seeking prosecution of terrorism suspects we use a range of tools at our disposal to manage the threat posed - including using the Royal Prerogative to withdraw British passport facilities, travel restrictions as part of imposing TPIMs on an individual, exclusion from the UK and deprivation of British citizenship where appropriate and using Schedule 1 to the Counter-Terrorism and Security Act 2015 to seize and temporarily retain travel documents.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-11-06T17:59:51.097Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778063/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778063/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778063/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-26","Islamic State: British Nationals Abroad","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how many British passport holders are known to have joined the military operations of the Islamic State; how many of those have returned to the UK; and whether they have the technical capability and the legal power to cancel electronically the passports of those concerned.","false","Biography information for Lord Marlesford",,"Lord Marlesford","HL2609"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778064","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-02","<p>The information requested is not readily available as it is not held centrally. It could be provided only at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>National Insurance numbers cannot be cancelled. This is because a National Insurance number, even if only used for a limited period, links an individual to their National Insurance contributions record which may be relevant in any future claim to benefits or State Pension.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2017-11-02T15:26:35.353Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778064/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778064/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778064/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-10-26","National Insurance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how many National Insurance numbers there are at present; and how many have been cancelled in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Lord Marlesford",,"Lord Marlesford","HL2610"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778065","Department for Transport","false","2017-11-03","<p>The independent Office of Rail and Road, as economic and safety regulator for the railway, is responsible for ensuring that Network Rail maintains and makes available an up-to-date and accurate asset register. This is enforced through condition 1 of the Network Licence. Government has no plans to impose a similar condition, as this would simply duplicate an existing requirement under the regulatory regime.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Sugg",,"2017-11-03T11:08:08.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778065/answer","Biography information for Baroness Sugg","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778065/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778065/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-10-26","Network Rail: Assets","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they have any plans to require Network Rail to publish and maintain an up-to-date and accurate database of assets, including gauge clearances of its network, along the lines described in the Scottish Governments High Level Output Statement for Control Period 6.","false","Biography information for Lord Berkeley",,"Lord Berkeley","HL2611"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778066","Cabinet Office","false","2017-11-09","<p>The 2015 National Security Strategy identifies cyber security as a tier one threat to the UK’s national security. To counter this threat the Government published the National Cyber Security Strategy 2016-2021 supported by £1.9billion of transformational investment. As part of the implementation of the strategy, a new National Cyber Security Centre was launched in 2016 to provide a central body for cyber security at a national level. In order to keep our cyber defences effective, the Government provides resources for research and development of technical and other measures, but it would not be appropriate to comment on specific technologies.</p>",,"Lord Young of Cookham",,"2017-11-09T16:07:26.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778066/answer","Biography information for Lord Young of Cookham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778066/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778066/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-10-26","Electronic Warfare","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they regard cyber warfare as a Tier One threat to national security; whether they are considering the creation of a new international Bletchley Park to counter that threat; and whether they are providing resources to develop machine learning algorithms and artificial intelligence to counter that threat.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL2612"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778068","Department of Health","false","2017-11-07","<p>We estimate the cost of providing termination of pregnancy services in England to women from Northern Ireland to be in the region of £1 million per year. The provision of antenatal and maternity services in Northern Ireland is a devolved matter. The decision to provide such funding is separate from issues about support for other groups of pregnant women and there is no necessary connection between the two matters.</p><p> </p><p>The Supreme Court in R (on the application of A and B) v Secretary of State for Health (2017) found that the Government has the power to fund abortion services in England for women lawfully resident from Northern Ireland.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2017-11-07T16:08:31.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778068/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778068/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778068/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-10-26","Abortion: Northern Ireland","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what is the estimated annual cost of payments from public funds to private sector abortion clinics in England to carry out abortions for patients from Northern Ireland; whether, under equalities and anti-discrimination legislation, there is a requirement for a similar level of resources to be made available to women who choose not to end their pregnancies; what assessment they have made of the estimate by Both Lives Matter that over 100,000 people are alive in Northern Ireland today, who would not be alive had the Abortion Act 1967 been applied there; and what advice they have sought from Law Officers about the lawfulness and the ethics of seeking to disregard in one part of the UK the lawful provisions applicable in another part of the UK.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL2613"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778069","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-11-06","<p>The Government is committed to making membership of a Client Money Protection scheme mandatory for letting and managing agents to ensure that tenants and landlords get the financial protection that they deserve. A consultation seeking views on implementation was launched on 1 November and will be open for 6 weeks. Further detail will be provided following consultation with the sector.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2017-11-06T17:57:46.63Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778069/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778069/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778069/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-26","Client Money Protection","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, following the announcement by Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth on 28 March (HL Deb, col 466), when they expect to legislate for a mandatory scheme of client money protection.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL2614"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778070","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-11-06","<p>We are committed to banning letting fees to improve transparency, affordability and competition in the private rental market. We published the draft Tenant Fees Bill and the response to the public consultation on banning tenant fees on 1 November. The draft Bill sets out the Government's implementation approach. Publishing the Bill in draft will enable further scrutiny of our proposals by Parliament and stakeholders, which will help to prevent any unintended negative consequences. We will provide more information on the implementation timetable following scrutiny of the draft Bill.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2017-11-06T17:58:06.81Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778070/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778070/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778070/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-26","Letting Agents: Fees and Charges","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government when they expect to legislate to ban lettings agent fees.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL2615"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778071","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-11-06","<p>There are no plans to set up pilot schemes to assess full cost recovery on planning applications by local authorities. However, we were clear in the Housing White Paper that properly resourced planning departments are an important part of delivering the new housing we need. That is why we are bringing forward regulations to increase planning application fees by 20 per cent. The Regulations to introduce the 20 per cent increase were laid on 19 October 2017 and will be considered by Committees of both Houses.</p><p>We are also currently consulting on the principle of introducing a further 20 per cent fee increase and how this could be applied in those authorities who are delivering the homes their communities need. A copy of the consultation (attached) can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/planning-for-the-right-homes-in-the-right-places-consultation-proposals" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/planning-for-the-right-homes-in-the-right-places-consultation-proposals</a></p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2017-11-06T16:11:30.15Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778071/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778071/answer","171030 Planning for Homes Consultation Document HL2616.pdf","171030 Planning for Homes Consultation Document HL2616.pdf","copy of the consultation","copy of the consultation","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778071/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-26","Planning Permission: Fees and Charges","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what plans, if any, they have to set up pilot schemes to assess full cost recovery on planning applications by local authorities.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL2616"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778072","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-11-06","<p>As I have indicated on previous occasions, we are continuing to discuss borrowing headroom with local authorities and we will be taking a pragmatic approach to these talks.</p><p>It would be unwise to prejudge the outcome of these discussions by attempting to list every circumstance under which we might agree to modify borrowing restrictions.</p><p>Fundamentally, the outcome of our talks with councils will depend on the financial position of each authority, the particular pressures in each locality and affordability from the wider national perspective.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2017-11-06T17:56:54.15Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778072/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778072/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778072/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-26","Local Government: Borrowing","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, further to the answers by Lord Young of Cookham on 25 October (HL Deb, col 935) and Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth on 26 October, what circumstances would lead them to lifting local authority borrowing restrictions.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL2617"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778073","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-11-06","<p>Starter homes form an important part of our ambition to help people onto the housing ladder, as set out in our Housing White Paper: Fixing Our Broken Housing Market. We have been clear that starter homes should be targeted at first-time buyers who would otherwise be priced out of the market. We have consulted on a minimum 10 per cent affordable home ownership national planning policy expectation for major sites and other planning reforms to deliver starter homes. We have also made good progress securing suitable brownfield sites through the Starter Homes Land Fund.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2017-11-06T17:57:20.923Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778073/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778073/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778073/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-26","Housing: Construction","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what progress has been made to date on the Starter Homes scheme.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL2618"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778074","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-11-06","<p>The Royal Air Force is due to take delivery of its first P-8A Poseidon maritime patrol aircraft in 2019, with the final one expected in 2021. We anticipate that the aircraft will then begin to operate from RAF Lossiemouth in 2020, with the fleet on track to be fully operational in 2024.</p>",,"Earl Howe","HL2621","2017-11-06T17:39:27.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778074/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778074/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778074/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-10-26","Maritime Patrol Aircraft","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government when they expect to take delivery of the first Boeing Poseidon P8 maritime patrol aircraft.","false","Biography information for Lord Campbell of Pittenweem",,"Lord Campbell of Pittenweem","HL2619"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778075","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-11-06","<p>Dedicated P-8A infrastructure will be developed at RAF Lossiemouth. This integrated facility, which is expected to be operational by 2021, will include accommodation for two front line squadrons, an operational conversion unit with simulators, maintenance hangars, and a mission support centre.</p><p>As commercial negotiations are still ongoing in relation to this infrastructure, I am withholding information relating to estimated costs as its disclosure would prejudice commercial interests.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2017-11-06T16:36:23.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778075/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778075/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778075/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-10-26","Maritime Patrol Aircraft","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what additional infrastructure will be required to accommodate the Boeing Poseidon P8 maritime patrol aircraft; and what is the estimated cost of doing so.","false","Biography information for Lord Campbell of Pittenweem",,"Lord Campbell of Pittenweem","HL2620"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778076","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-11-06","<p>The Royal Air Force is due to take delivery of its first P-8A Poseidon maritime patrol aircraft in 2019, with the final one expected in 2021. We anticipate that the aircraft will then begin to operate from RAF Lossiemouth in 2020, with the fleet on track to be fully operational in 2024.</p>",,"Earl Howe","HL2619","2017-11-06T17:39:27.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778076/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778076/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778076/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-10-26","Maritime Patrol Aircraft","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government when they expect that the fleet of Boeing Poseidon P8 maritime aircraft will be fully operational.","false","Biography information for Lord Campbell of Pittenweem",,"Lord Campbell of Pittenweem","HL2621"
