"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778289","Scotland Office","false","2017-10-31","<p>I meet regularly with Cabinet colleagues and discuss a wide range of matters. Geographical indications are important to our reputation as a great food nation. As we leave the EU, the UK will continue to abide by WTO rules on the protection of geographical indications globally, and we will prioritise continued protection of the best of our UK food and drink as we consider future trade opportunities across the world.</p><p> </p><p>Countries outside the EU are already able to participate in the EU's geographical indication schemes when selling onto the EU market. In addition, the EU rules that currently govern the enforcement of geographical indications will be placed on a UK legal basis through the EU Withdrawal Bill.</p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell","109827 ; 109837 ; 109838 ; 109839 ; 109840 ; 109841 ; 109980 ; 109981","2017-10-31T11:17:16.18Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778289/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778289/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778289/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2017-10-26","Whisky: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what recent discussions he has had with the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union on the protection of intellectual property rights for Scotch whisky in any trade deal with the EU after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Hannah Bardell","Livingston","Hannah Bardell","110001"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778290","Department for Transport","false","2017-11-03","<p>The Department continues to engage with a wide range of stakeholders on the delivery of the Cycling and Walking Investment Strategy. I met with representatives from the main walking and cycling organisations on 19 September to discuss various matters including how the Department might best benefit from their expertise in delivering the strategy, and have met regularly with Cycling and Walking stakeholders since then. In the light of this discussion, the Department has decided to establish a more informal stakeholder advisory group to ensure that cycling and walking policies are informed by regular dialogue with the relevant organisations. I will be meeting regularly with the group myself so that I can listen to and consider their views.</p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-11-03T12:41:37.95Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778290/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778290/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778290/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-10-26","Cycling and Walking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the timetable is for the appointment of the Chair and expert panel of the Cycling and Walking Investment Strategy.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","109991"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778291","Department for Transport","false","2017-11-03","<p>The Highway Code already gives advice to look out for other road users when turning. When the Department carries out the next revision to the Code it will as usual undertake a consultation on any proposed changes. The forthcoming Cycle Safety Review may offer an opportunity to review proposals and evidence on this matter in relation to cyclists.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-11-03T12:45:43.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778291/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778291/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778291/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-10-26","Highway Code","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will bring forward legislative proposals to review the Highway Code so that motorists are obliged to give way on turning into or out of side roads to protect people crossing those roads.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","110009"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778292","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-31","<p>Highways England undertook a risk assessment of the concept of 60mph in roadworks, and has trialed it at several sites. Each site had a specific risk assessment before the trial started.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-10-31T17:41:25.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778292/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778292/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/778292/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-10-26","Road Works: Speed Limits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the safety implications of raising the 50 mph limit through road works on the motorway network to 60 mph.","false","Biography information for Mike Amesbury","Weaver Vale","Mike Amesbury","109888"
